="en" data-exc=""><p><span style="font-weight: 700; color: rgb(221, 51, 51);">Could be better:</span></p></div></div><div data-label="Icon List" data-key="icon-list" data-atomgroup="module" id="m-1698606543096" class="module-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-iconlist" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1698606543096"><div class="module gf_module-left gf_module-left-lg gf_module--md gf_module--sm gf_module--xs "><ul class="gf_icon-list"><li style="margin-bottom: 15px"><span class="gf-il-icon item-content" data-index="1" data-key="content" style="width: 45px"><div data-label="Icon" id="e-1698606543096-1" class="element-wrap" data-id="1698606543096-1" data-icon="gpicon-icon" data-ver="1.0"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><div class="gf_icon-wrap" style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(221, 51, 51);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-close"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="1" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1698606543096-2" class="element-wrap" data-id="1698606543096-2"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-exc=""><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">More suitable for smaller lifters or bench press specialists</p></div></div></div></li><li style="margin-bottom: 15px"><span class="gf-il-icon item-content" data-index="2" data-key="content" style="width: 45px"><div data-label="Icon" id="e-1698606576513" class="element-wrap" data-id="1698606576513" data-icon="gpicon-icon" data-ver="1.0"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><div class="gf_icon-wrap" style="font-size: 20px; color: rgb(221, 51, 51);"><i class="gf_icon fa fa-close"></i></div></div></div></span><div class="gf-il-content item-content" data-index="2" data-key="content1" style="padding-left: 45px"><div data-label="Text Block" id="e-1698606576477" class="element-wrap" data-id="1698606576477"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-exc=""><p style="text-align: inherit!important;">Not as widely produced as 4-inch belts</p></div></div></div></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1698608104038" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1698608104038"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Who Needs a 3-Inch Lifting Belt?</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1661923936590" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1661923936590"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h4 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">1. Shorter Lifters</h4></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1659008080559" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1659008080559" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><span style="color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: inherit; text-align: inherit; letter-spacing: 0px;">If you're a shorter lifter with a smaller torso, wearing a 4-inch belt may be uncomfortable to use by digging into your torso during lifting.</span><br></p><p>This may make the 3-inch belt a better option, allowing increased range of motion and flexibility when lifting, allowing you to focus on proper bracing and technique and increase your lifts.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1661924211524" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1661924211524"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h4 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">2. Bench Press Specialists&nbsp;</h4></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1661924317281" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1661924317281" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><span style="color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: inherit; text-align: inherit; letter-spacing: 0px;">If you're a bench press specialist competing in bench press competitions, the 3-inch belt size may be a better choice.</span><br></p><p><span style="color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: inherit; text-align: inherit; letter-spacing: 0px;">When performing a bench press, you only need to support your lower back. The mid-back needs to flex and arch backward, meaning the 4-inch belt may be uncomfortable and limit your range of movement.</span></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1661936213383" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1661936213383"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h4 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">3. Fitness athlete</h4></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1661924350146" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1661924350146" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><span style="color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: inherit; text-align: inherit; letter-spacing: 0px;">If you're a fitness athlete, most exercises are performed using a full range of movement meaning you may benefit from the increased flexibility the 3-inch belt offers.</span><br></p><p>Fitness generally involves multiple different types of lifts and Olympic movements, making the 3-inch belt an ideal choice.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1698609518994" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1698609518994" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-exc=""><a href="Lifting Belt in Use" target=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/af37834c-fa7d-479c-9acd-b6953c02c462/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/lifting%20belt%20wbcm%20men.png" alt="Lifting Belt in Use" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></a></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1660101672311" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1660101672311"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Pros and Cons of 4 Inch Lifting Belts</span></h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1660101675819" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1660101675819" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gem