lement" id="e-1659008080602" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1659008080602"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">How thick should a weightlifting belt be?</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1660101495259" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1660101495259"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit!important; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">The thickness of your lifting belt depends mostly on your ability level and goals. A 10 mm belt would be a better choice if you're a recreational lifter as it's more comfortable, offers increased flexibility, and doesn't take as long to break-in.</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit!important; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">If you are an elite level lifter, using a 13mm belt may give that extra bit of performance needed despite being less flexible and harder to ‘break in’</p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit!important; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"></p><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit!important; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1659008080605" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1659008080605"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-